BPF system call :
        the system call BPF is newly added into kernel,it performs a range of
        operations related to "extended Berkeley Packet(eBPF) Filters".
        the "classic BPF is used to filter network packets",eBPF is some kind
        of that,but it extends cBPF in multiple ways.
                ability to call a fixed set of in-kernel helper functions
                access shared data structures such as eBPF maps

        User Mode header is
                <linux/bpf.h>
        Prototype of User Mode interface is
                int bpf(int cmd, union bpf_attr *attr, unsigned int size);

        both cBPF and eBPF programs,are statically analyzed by kernel before
        loading them.
        
        BPF maps,are a generic data structure for storage of different data types.
        data type is treated at an binary blob,when creating map,user must
        specifies the size of the key and the size of the value.
                [key, value]
                # requires size,the exact structure type is opaque.
        BPF maps can be accessed through a file descriptor,when the process who
        created the map is exit,the file descriptor will be closed,thus the BPF
        map will be destroyed.(but there is a way to leave them alive)
        different eBPF programs can access the same maps in parallel.

        eBPF special map type,the program array,in which,file descriptors are
        stored,and the file descriptor associated with other eBPF programs.
        if an eBPF program performs a lookup on the array,the program's
        execution flow is redirected in-place to the beginning of that eBPF
        program current file descriptor associated with,and the execution flow
        would not return back to the old eBPF program.in the new eBPF program,
        it can also execute the old program again from its beginning,but there
        is a recursion limiter that fixed to 32 times.
        file descriptor in program array can be modified at runtime,thus we
        can get flexibility to change behaviors based on specific requirements.
           +--> Kernel eBPF Virtual Machine
           |
           |    eBPF_program1:
           |            ...
           |            performs a lookup
           |                            |        
           |                            |--> eBPF_program_idx0 --> jmp to beginning
           |                            |                          |
           |                            |--> ...                   |
           |                            .                          |
           |                            .                          V # execution
           |                            .                          .
           |            ... # rest      |                          .
           |                            |                          .
           |                            V                          |
           +-------------------------------------------------------+ # return path
           /**
            * This jumping usually happens call to bpf_tail_call().
            * The helper needs a context pointer,a bpf_map descriptor,and an index
            * to the program array.
            * If the tail calling can be executed,the execution flow of current
            * eBPF program would be modified in-place to the new eBPF program's
            * beginning,and the old eBPF program would not return(not function call),
            * we will return from the new eBPF program.
            * if we can not execute the new eBPF program,then the old program
            * continue to executes instructions after bpf_tail_call(),like
            * the default control path.
            * when we construct such program through bytecodes,there is mandatory
            * to modify the value in bpf_reg0 before call to bpf exit;otherwise,
            * R0 !read_ok will throw.
            * ! when construct eBPF program,the last opcode must be jump instruction
            *   or exit calling instruction.
            *   call to the helper that will return back is not legal at the
            *   last opcode.
            * ! bpf_tail_call() has recursion limit,the maximum value is 32.
            */
    
        eBPF program that associated with the file descriptor in program array
        must be loaded into kernel previously,if lookup failed,the old eBPF
        program will continue its execution.
        /* eBPF program usually is loaded by userspace process,and unloaded
         * when the process exit,but leave them alive through tc-bpf.
         * when the process exit,tc-bpf will holds references to the eBPF
         * program to prevent from kernel destroy them.
         */

        each eBPF program is a set of instructions that is safe to run until
        its completion,in-kernel verifier statically determines that the
        eBPF program terminates and is safe to execute.
        /* kernel gets ref to the eBPF program during verification */
        
        each eBPF program can be attached to different events
                arrival of network packets
                tracing events
                classification events by network queueing disciplines
                ...
        when a new event comes,it triggers execution to the eBPF program
        attached to it.the same eBPF program can be attached to multiple
        events and different eBPF programs can access the same map.
        /* thus we can sharing data between different eBPF programs */
        
